==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Defence
<hw>De*fence"</hw> }</mhw> <pr>(?)</pr>,
<pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F. <ets>d⟦eacute⟧fense</ets>, OF.
<ets>defense</ets>, fem., <ets>defens</ets>, masc., fr. L.
<ets>defensa</ets> (cf. LL. <ets>defensum</ets>), from
<ets>defendere</ets>. See <er>Defend</er>, and cf.
<er>Fence</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of defending, or the
state of being defended; protection, as from violence or
danger.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In cases of <qex>defense</qex> 't is best to weigh⟦br⟧
The enemy more mighty than he seems.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which defends or protects; anything employed to
oppose attack, ward off violence or danger, or maintain security; a
guard; a protection.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>War would arise in <qex>defense</qex> of the right.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>God, the widow's champion and <qex>defense</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Protecting plea; vindication;
justification.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Men, brethren, and fathers, hear ye my <qex>defense</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Acts xxii. 1.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>The defendant's answer or plea; an
opposing or denial of the truth or validity of the plaintiff's or
prosecutor's case; the method of proceeding adopted by the defendant to
protect himself against the plaintiff's action.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>Act or skill in making defense; defensive plan or
policy; practice in self defense, as in fencing, boxing, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A man of great <qex>defense</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>By how much <qex>defense</qex> is better than no skill.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>Prohibition; a prohibitory ordinance.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Severe <qex>defenses</qex> . . . against wearing any linen under a
certain breadth.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W. Temple.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Defense</ent>⟦br⟧
